{
  "What process is used in nuclear power plants to generate energy?": "",
  "Chemical combustion": "",
  "Radioactive decay only": "",
  "Nuclear fission": "",
  "Nuclear fusion": "",
  "Nuclear power plants use nuclear fission, the splitting of heavy atomic nuclei (typically uranium-235 or plutonium-239) into smaller nuclei, releasing enormous amounts of energy that heats water to produce steam for driving turbines.": "",
  "What is the primary fuel used in most nuclear power plants?": "",
  "Hydrogen-2 (deuterium)": "",
  "Uranium-235": "",
  "Thorium-232": "",
  "Plutonium-239": "",
  "Uranium-235 is the primary fuel in most commercial nuclear reactors because it is the only naturally occurring isotope that is readily fissile, meaning it can sustain a chain reaction when bombarded with neutrons.": "",
  "What is the most significant long-term environmental concern with nuclear energy?": "",
  "Safe storage of radioactive waste for thousands of years": "",
  "Noise pollution from turbines": "",
  "Excessive water consumption compared to all other energy sources": "",
  "Carbon dioxide emissions during operation": "",
  "High-level radioactive waste from nuclear power plants remains dangerously radioactive for thousands to hundreds of thousands of years, requiring secure long-term storage solutions that have not yet been fully implemented anywhere in the world.": "",
  "What happened at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in 1986?": "",
  "A successful fusion experiment was conducted": "",
  "A minor leak was quickly contained with no consequences": "",
  "The plant was peacefully decommissioned": "",
  "A catastrophic reactor explosion released massive amounts of radioactive material into the environment": "",
  "The Chernobyl disaster was the worst nuclear accident in history, caused by a flawed reactor design and operator error during a safety test; the explosion and fire released large quantities of radioactive material across Europe, contaminating vast areas and causing long-term health effects.": "",
  "What is one major advantage of nuclear power compared to fossil fuels?": "",
  "It requires no specialized safety measures": "",
  "It uses only renewable resources": "",
  "It generates electricity without producing greenhouse gas emissions during operation": "",
  "It produces large amounts of CO2 during operation": "",
  "Nuclear power plants produce virtually no greenhouse gas emissions during electricity generation, making them a low-carbon energy source; the lifecycle emissions (including mining, construction, and decommissioning) are comparable to wind and solar.": "",
  "What caused the Fukushima nuclear disaster in 2011?": "",
  "Operator error during routine maintenance": "",
  "A design flaw in the reactor": "",
  "A terrorist attack on the facility": "",
  "A massive earthquake and tsunami that overwhelmed the plant's safety systems": "",
  "The Fukushima Daiichi disaster was triggered by a magnitude 9.0 earthquake and subsequent tsunami that disabled the plant's cooling systems, leading to three reactor meltdowns and the release of radioactive material, forcing the evacuation of over 150,000 people.": "",
  "What is nuclear fusion?": "",
  "The splitting of heavy atoms to release energy": "",
  "The combining of light atomic nuclei to form heavier nuclei, releasing enormous energy": "",
  "The chemical burning of uranium fuel": "",
  "The decay of radioactive elements over time": "",
  "Nuclear fusion is the process of combining light nuclei (such as hydrogen isotopes) to form heavier nuclei, releasing tremendous energy; it powers the sun and could theoretically provide nearly limitless clean energy, but sustained controlled fusion has not yet been achieved commercially.": "",
  "What is a nuclear meltdown?": "",
  "The uncontrolled overheating and melting of nuclear fuel due to failure of cooling systems": "",
  "A controlled release of steam from a reactor": "",
  "The natural aging of nuclear fuel rods": "",
  "The planned shutdown of a nuclear reactor": "",
  "A nuclear meltdown occurs when cooling systems fail and the heat from nuclear fission causes fuel to melt, potentially breaching containment structures and releasing radioactive material; it is the most feared type of nuclear accident.": "",
  "What is the half-life of a radioactive isotope?": "",
  "Half the lifespan of the nuclear power plant": "",
  "Half the time a nuclear waste container will last": "",
  "The time it takes to produce half the fuel needed": "",
  "The time it takes for half the atoms in a radioactive sample to decay": "",
  "The half-life is the time required for half of the atoms in a radioactive sample to undergo decay; half-lives vary enormously between isotopes, from fractions of a second to billions of years, determining how long nuclear waste remains hazardous.": "",
  "How does a nuclear power plant generate electricity?": "",
  "By using heat from nuclear fission to produce steam that drives turbines connected to generators": "",
  "By converting uranium directly into electrical current": "",
  "By using nuclear reactions to create wind that spins turbines": "",
  "By directly converting radiation into electricity": "",
  "Nuclear power plants use the heat generated by nuclear fission to boil water and produce high-pressure steam; this steam drives turbines connected to electrical generators, similar to how coal and gas plants work but with nuclear fuel instead of fossil fuels.": "",
  "What does 'nuclear fission' mean?": "",
  "The chemical reaction between uranium and water": "",
  "The combining of light atoms to form heavier ones": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy atomic nucleus into two or more lighter nuclei, releasing a large amount of energy": "",
  "The natural erosion of rock containing uranium": "",
  "Nuclear fission is the process in which a heavy nucleus (like uranium-235) absorbs a neutron and splits into two smaller nuclei, releasing energy, additional neutrons, and radiation; the released neutrons can trigger further fissions in a chain reaction.": "",
  "What does 'radioactive waste' refer to?": "",
  "Waste material that contains radioactive isotopes and emits ionizing radiation, requiring special handling and storage": "",
  "Unused uranium fuel that has not been placed in a reactor": "",
  "Waste water used for cooling nuclear reactors": "",
  "Any waste produced by a nuclear power plant, including office paper": "",
  "Radioactive waste is material contaminated with radioactive isotopes that emit harmful ionizing radiation; it is classified as low-level (protective clothing, tools), intermediate-level (reactor components), or high-level (spent fuel), each requiring different disposal methods.": "",
  "What is 'nuclear proliferation'?": "",
  "The growth of public support for nuclear energy": "",
  "The rapid construction of nuclear power plants": "",
  "The natural multiplication of radioactive atoms": "",
  "The spread of nuclear weapons or weapons-capable nuclear technology and materials to additional countries": "",
  "Nuclear proliferation refers to the spread of nuclear weapons, weapons-usable material, or weapons technology to nations that do not currently possess them; the dual-use nature of nuclear technology (civilian power and weapons) makes proliferation a persistent security concern.": "",
  "What does 'spent nuclear fuel' mean?": "",
  "Natural uranium ore before processing": "",
  "Fuel that has completely lost all radioactivity": "",
  "Fuel that has been used in a reactor and can no longer sustain a chain reaction efficiently, but remains highly radioactive": "",
  "Nuclear fuel that was purchased but never used": "",
  "Spent nuclear fuel is fuel that has been used in a reactor until it can no longer efficiently sustain fission; it remains intensely radioactive and thermally hot, containing fission products and actinides that require careful management for thousands of years.": "",
  "What does 'chain reaction' mean in nuclear physics?": "",
  "The sequence of steps in building a nuclear reactor": "",
  "A series of chemical reactions in a chain-link pattern": "",
  "A self-sustaining series of nuclear fissions where neutrons released from one fission event trigger additional fissions": "",
  "The chain of command in a nuclear power plant": "",
  "A nuclear chain reaction occurs when neutrons released by one fission event cause additional fissions in nearby nuclei, releasing more neutrons in a self-sustaining process; in reactors, this chain reaction is carefully controlled to maintain a steady energy output.": "",
  "What is 'enrichment' in the context of nuclear fuel?": "",
  "Mixing uranium with other metals to make it stronger": "",
  "The financial profit from operating a nuclear plant": "",
  "The process of increasing the concentration of the fissile isotope uranium-235 in uranium fuel": "",
  "Adding vitamins and minerals to uranium for safety": "",
  "Uranium enrichment increases the proportion of the fissile isotope U-235 from its natural abundance of 0.7% to 3-5% for reactor fuel (or over 90% for weapons); the enrichment process is both technically complex and a proliferation concern.": "",
  "What does 'decommissioning' mean for a nuclear power plant?": "",
  "Starting up a new nuclear reactor for the first time": "",
  "Upgrading a nuclear plant to produce more power": "",
  "Transferring ownership of a nuclear plant to a new company": "",
  "The process of safely shutting down, dismantling, and cleaning up a nuclear facility at the end of its operational life": "",
  "Decommissioning is the complex, expensive, and time-consuming process of safely shutting down a nuclear facility, removing fuel and radioactive materials, decontaminating structures, and managing waste, which can take decades and cost billions of dollars.": "",
  "What is a 'control rod' in a nuclear reactor?": "",
  "A neutron-absorbing rod that is inserted into or withdrawn from the reactor core to regulate the rate of the fission chain reaction": "",
  "A rod made of uranium that provides fuel to the reactor": "",
  "A structural support rod that holds the reactor in place": "",
  "A rod used to measure the temperature of the reactor": "",
  "Control rods are made of neutron-absorbing materials (like boron or cadmium) that can be inserted into or withdrawn from the reactor core to control the rate of the nuclear chain reaction; inserting them slows the reaction, and removing them speeds it up.": "",
  "What is 'containment' in nuclear safety?": "",
  "The container used to transport fresh fuel to the plant": "",
  "The budget allocated for nuclear plant construction": "",
  "The process of containing public information about nuclear plants": "",
  "The system of physical barriers, including the reactor vessel and building, designed to prevent the release of radioactive material": "",
  "Containment in nuclear safety refers to the multiple physical barriers (fuel cladding, reactor pressure vessel, and containment building) designed to prevent radioactive material from escaping into the environment under both normal and accident conditions.": "",
  "What does 'breeder reactor' mean?": "",
  "A nuclear reactor that produces more fissile material than it consumes by converting non-fissile isotopes into fissile fuel": "",
  "A reactor designed to breed fish near power plant cooling water": "",
  "A reactor that generates electricity using wind power": "",
  "A small reactor used for research purposes only": "",
  "A breeder reactor is designed to convert non-fissile material (like uranium-238 or thorium-232) into fissile material (plutonium-239 or uranium-233) faster than it consumes fuel, potentially extending nuclear fuel supplies significantly but raising proliferation concerns.": "",
  "The United States has accumulated over 80,000 metric tons of spent nuclear fuel stored at reactor sites across the country because no permanent geological repository has been completed. The proposed Yucca Mountain repository in Nevada was cancelled due to political opposition. What does this situation illustrate about nuclear waste management?": "",
  "Spent fuel can be safely stored at reactor sites indefinitely without risk": "",
  "Nuclear waste is no longer radioactive after 10 years": "",
  "The technical and political challenges of siting permanent nuclear waste storage make it one of the most intractable environmental problems": "",
  "Nuclear waste storage is a solved problem": "",
  "Despite decades of scientific study confirming that deep geological repositories can safely store waste, no country has yet opened a permanent facility (though Finland is close) due to intense political opposition, public fear, and the NIMBY (Not In My Backyard) phenomenon.": "",
  "After the Fukushima disaster in 2011, Germany decided to phase out all nuclear power by 2022, replacing it with renewable energy and, temporarily, natural gas and coal. Japan shut down all 54 of its reactors for safety reviews. What do these different national responses reveal about nuclear energy policy?": "",
  "Fukushima had no impact on nuclear energy policy worldwide": "",
  "All countries responded identically to Fukushima": "",
  "Nuclear energy policy is heavily influenced by public perception and political factors, not just technical risk assessment": "",
  "Nuclear energy is too dangerous to use anywhere": "",
  "The varied national responses to Fukushima show that nuclear energy decisions involve complex trade-offs between energy security, climate goals, economic factors, public perception, and risk tolerance; different societies weigh these factors differently based on their political and cultural contexts.": "",
  "Climate scientists note that nuclear power provides about 10% of global electricity with virtually no operational carbon emissions. Some argue that meeting climate targets is impossible without expanding nuclear power, while others say the risks and costs make it unnecessary given declining renewable energy prices. What is the core of this debate?": "",
  "Nuclear power produces more CO2 than coal": "",
  "All scientists agree that nuclear power should be eliminated immediately": "",
  "Whether the low-carbon benefits of nuclear power outweigh its risks, costs, and waste management challenges compared to alternatives": "",
  "Nuclear power has no role in addressing climate change": "",
  "The nuclear energy debate centers on trade-offs: it provides reliable, low-carbon baseload power but comes with high construction costs, waste storage challenges, accident risks, and proliferation concerns; whether it is essential for climate goals or can be replaced by renewables remains a major policy question.": "",
  "France generates approximately 70% of its electricity from nuclear power and has some of the lowest electricity-related carbon emissions in Europe. In contrast, Germany, which phased out nuclear power, has higher emissions and relies partly on coal. What does this comparison suggest about nuclear energy and emissions reduction?": "",
  "Nuclear power has no effect on carbon emissions, since the prevailing theory about nuclear would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "France and Germany have identical carbon emissions from electricity in most scenarios involving nuclear factors": "",
  "Germany's approach produced lower emissions than France's within the broader context of nuclear analysis": "",
  "Nuclear power can be effective at reducing electricity-sector emissions, and phasing it out may increase reliance on fossil fuels if renewables cannot fully replace it immediately": "",
  "France's heavy nuclear reliance gives it very low electricity emissions, while Germany's nuclear phase-out, despite massive renewable investment, has been partially offset by continued coal use; this illustrates that replacing nuclear with renewables must happen fast enough to avoid increased fossil fuel dependence.": "",
  "Small modular reactors (SMRs) are being developed as a new generation of nuclear technology. They are factory-built, smaller than traditional reactors, and designed with passive safety systems. What potential advantage do SMRs offer over conventional large nuclear plants?": "",
  "They are powered by solar energy rather than uranium": "",
  "They produce no radioactive waste of any kind": "",
  "Lower upfront costs, faster construction, enhanced safety features, and flexibility for deployment in smaller grids": "",
  "They are completely risk-free with zero chance of any accident": "",
  "SMRs aim to address traditional nuclear challenges: factory fabrication reduces costs and construction time, passive safety systems reduce accident risk by relying on natural processes rather than active systems, and their smaller size makes them suitable for smaller grids and remote locations.": "",
  "The Chernobyl exclusion zone, evacuated after the 1986 disaster, has unexpectedly become a wildlife haven, with populations of wolves, wild horses, deer, and lynx thriving in the absence of humans. What does this surprising ecological recovery tell us about radiation and ecosystems?": "",
  "The removal of human activity can benefit wildlife even in contaminated areas, though individual organisms may still suffer radiation effects": "",
  "Radiation is beneficial for wildlife": "",
  "Animals are completely immune to all forms of radiation": "",
  "The Chernobyl exclusion zone has no radiation remaining": "",
  "The Chernobyl wildlife recovery suggests that for many species, the absence of human disturbance (farming, hunting, development) outweighs the negative effects of radiation; while individual animals may have elevated mutation rates and health issues, populations as a whole have rebounded in the human-free zone.": "",
  "A coastal city considers building a nuclear power plant to replace aging coal plants and reduce carbon emissions. Residents oppose the plan, citing fears of a Fukushima-style disaster. The utility argues that modern reactor designs have passive safety systems. What should inform the decision about whether to build the plant?": "",
  "Public fear alone should determine energy policy, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Nuclear power should never be built near any coast regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "A comprehensive risk-benefit analysis considering safety features, seismic and flood risk, waste management, alternatives, and public engagement": "",
  "Only the financial cost should be considered, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Sound nuclear energy decisions require comprehensive analysis: evaluating site-specific hazards (seismic, flooding), reactor safety features, waste management plans, comparison with alternative energy options, economic costs, and meaningful public engagement to address legitimate concerns with accurate information.": "",
  "Finland is constructing the world's first permanent geological repository for spent nuclear fuel at Onkalo, designed to safely store waste for at least 100,000 years in stable bedrock 400 meters underground. What engineering and geological requirements make deep geological disposal the preferred long-term waste solution?": "",
  "The waste only needs to be stored for 10 years before it is safe": "",
  "The repository can be built in any type of rock at any depth": "",
  "Underground storage is the cheapest possible option": "",
  "Stable geology, multiple engineered barriers, isolation from groundwater, and passive safety that does not require ongoing human maintenance": "",
  "Deep geological repositories rely on multiple barriers: stable bedrock that has been geologically undisturbed for millions of years, engineered barriers (copper canisters, bentonite clay), isolation from water flow, and passive safety that does not depend on human monitoring or intervention over geological timescales.": "",
  "A developing country with growing energy needs considers nuclear power for the first time. The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) outlines prerequisites including regulatory frameworks, trained personnel, security infrastructure, and waste management plans. Why are these prerequisites important?": "",
  "These requirements only apply to weapons programs, not power plants": "",
  "Nuclear power requires robust institutional capacity to ensure safe operations, prevent proliferation, manage waste, and protect public safety": "",
  "Any country can safely operate nuclear reactors without preparation": "",
  "These are optional and not needed for nuclear power": "",
  "Nuclear power requires an extensive supporting infrastructure beyond the reactor itself: independent safety regulators, trained operators and scientists, security systems to prevent theft of nuclear material, emergency response capability, and long-term waste management plans, all of which take years to develop.": "",
  "Nuclear fusion, if achieved at commercial scale, could provide virtually limitless clean energy from hydrogen isotopes extracted from water. Despite decades of research and billions in investment, commercial fusion power remains elusive. What is the primary technical challenge preventing commercial fusion?": "",
  "Scientists do not understand how fusion works, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Fusion produces more radioactive waste than fission, as conventional fusion theory would suggest": "",
  "Sustaining the extreme temperatures and pressures needed for fusion (over 100 million degrees) while producing more energy than is consumed by the process": "",
  "There is not enough hydrogen on Earth for fusion when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The core challenge of fusion is achieving 'ignition': maintaining plasma at over 100 million degrees Celsius in a stable confinement for long enough that the fusion reactions produce more energy than is required to heat and contain the plasma, a condition called net energy gain.": ""
